arch:property.oc:show_val: L37 is a pebble and potsherd surface below the hard clayey loam in L33. This is a surface similar to the ones in L30 and L32. This is the best preserved surface of the three and it does not extend all the way to the east baulk but stops abruptly at L36. We found a lot of lithics, blades and obsidian. We also took two microanalysis samples and the rest of the surface was separated into artifact bags and screened 1/1. After we cleaned off the surface we closed L37 and opened L40 as fill below the surface.
very hard compacted clayey loam, medium and fine grain
lots of pebbles and pot sherds, lithics, and obsidian, some bone
this surface is stamped into the compacted clayey fill and is uniform throughout

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
